I started out at the new school for social research in New York City and then moved to

01:10.720 --> 01:16.800
University of Utah and Salt Lake City and then finished up my PhD at the University of South

01:16.800 --> 01:25.520
Florida in Tampa, where I studied with a very important figure in existential philosophy,

01:25.520 --> 01:32.800
an especially Heidegger, a fellow named Charles Guillaume, who sadly passed away this past summer,

01:33.440 --> 01:41.200
but had a long and influential career and taught a lot of students. And so that's that's the brief

01:41.200 --> 01:48.640
condensed version of who I am. And I consider myself a specialist in existential philosophy,

01:49.520 --> 01:56.960
phenomenology of the body, and areas of existential psychotherapy and phenomenological

01:56.960 --> 02:05.520
psychotherapy. Now, phenomenology of the body is not something that I come across people saying

02:05.520 --> 02:14.240
a lot as their specialties. Yeah, yeah, it's a it's a it's a booming field right now. It's

02:14.240 --> 02:22.240
largely indebted to the renewed interest in the work of Maurice Meryl Ponte and some important

02:22.240 --> 02:31.360
and seminal feminist figures, obviously, Simone de Beauvoir, one and Iris Marion Young, another

02:31.360 --> 02:39.360
figure. And it's simply a recognition that the body is not something we have, and that we're

02:39.360 --> 02:47.200
only contingently connected to. It's who we are, we are our bodies, we exist through our bodies,

02:47.200 --> 02:53.360
we live through the vehicle of our bodies. And so it's an attempt to undermine that classic

02:53.360 --> 03:00.320
Cartesian dualism that the human being is composed of two distinct substances and an immaterial mind

03:00.320 --> 03:07.920
in a causally determined body. And phenomenology undoes that dualism in helpful ways.

03:12.480 --> 03:19.680
So you spoke slightly about your your kind of academic journey into this amazing field of

03:19.680 --> 03:26.880
philosophy and of existentialism. But what drew you to want to specialize in existentialism in

