04:43.360 --> 04:53.840
God, the problems of nihilism, the experiences of anxiety and the face of death. And it awakened

04:53.840 --> 05:00.720
me to the fact that I've had these experiences. I feel this in my everyday life. And I changed

05:00.720 --> 05:07.840
my major to philosophy and never looked back. And many other aspects of philosophy I find

05:08.000 --> 05:15.440
uninteresting and boring, metaphysics and epistemology, even much of ethics, moral philosophy,

05:15.440 --> 05:29.280
I find boring and turgid. But existentialism always inspired me and shaped me. And it has stayed

05:29.280 --> 05:39.120
with me since I was 18 or 19 years old. And I had powerful experiences in my early adulthood and

05:39.120 --> 05:46.240
late adolescence of hanging out with my high school friends, you know, getting high and having a few

05:46.240 --> 05:52.240
beers under the stars, and talking about the meaning of life. And what is it all about? And who are

05:52.240 --> 05:59.280
we? And why are we here? And I realized that those were the questions of the existentials, right?

05:59.280 --> 06:06.400
Those are deep and important existential questions. And unfortunately, as we move into adulthood and

06:06.400 --> 06:13.760
find our way into careers and family life, we oftentimes lose touch with those important

06:13.760 --> 06:20.320
questions. And we kind of drift along in our existence until there's a crisis or a breakdown.

06:20.320 --> 06:28.000
And suddenly we wake up again to how important existential thinking is. And so that has kind

06:28.000 --> 06:36.560
of been the arc of my life. It's always been shaped and informed by an existential attitude or an

06:36.560 --> 06:46.480
existential orientation. It sounds like you genuinely connected with the kind of existential

06:46.560 --> 06:52.800
questions and never were able to kind of shake them away rather than stumbling across

06:52.800 --> 07:00.080
a textbook in a formalized module and saying, okay, I better learn this theory. You've felt the

07:00.080 --> 07:08.320
questions within you. That was a visceral experience. It wasn't about a vocation. It wasn't

07:08.320 --> 07:14.560
about even getting a job as a philosophy professor. It was about a way of existing. And so I would be

07:14.560 --> 07:21.520
doing existentialism if I was managing a restaurant or working in middle management somewhere for a

07:21.520 --> 07:26.800
company. I would still be watching existential films, listening to existential music,

07:28.080 --> 07:36.240
reading existential poetry and all of the things that move me, as you say, viscerally or in a

07:36.240 --> 07:46.080
mooted way. Because they speak to the concerns at the core of our condition. These are the ultimate

07:46.080 --> 07:54.640
concerns of our lives. And so yeah, they've had a powerful orienting impact on me.

07:58.240 --> 08:05.200
You bring up something for me, which is the fact that you're going through that phase of life when

08:05.200 --> 08:10.400
you're younger and you're chatting with your friends and you're asking these massive, massive

08:10.400 --> 08:15.840
questions, these really deep questions. And then you fade into a life where you're not

08:15.840 --> 08:20.320
what you're not supposed to be asking these questions. I remember for me, I don't know about

08:20.320 --> 08:27.280
you, but it was kind of almost stigmatized to ask why rather than to just follow, to question

08:27.280 --> 08:32.000
these deep meanings rather than to just pick a career and follow it. I don't know if you can relate

08:32.080 --> 08:40.160
to that. Oh, certainly I can. And it's, you know, just because we are kind of sucked into

08:41.040 --> 08:47.840
the shallows of social convention and go with the flow of everyday life, the existentialists

08:47.840 --> 08:54.240
make it clear that that's not a moral failing. It's not as if you're doing something wrong. It's just

08:54.960 --> 09:01.920
part of the inertia of being human, that we're always going to be, Heidegger has this

09:02.640 --> 09:09.840
language of temptation, we're tempted by the they or the public world, because it's comfortable,

09:09.840 --> 09:18.240
it's predictable, it's well ordered, and it covers over the anxiety, that kind of quivering

09:18.240 --> 09:26.640
unease, that all human beings experience an unease that reminds us that there's something wrong

09:26.640 --> 09:34.640
with us, that there's something disconnected or out of sync with us and the world. And it's

09:34.640 --> 09:38.880
because we're conscious, it's because we're self aware that we're aware that we're going to die,

09:38.880 --> 09:48.080
we're aware that God is dead, and there are no moral absolutes. And so I think existentialists

09:48.080 --> 09:57.120
are just deeply attuned to the fragility and weakness of human beings, that we drift to religion,

09:57.120 --> 10:03.200
we drift to comfort, we drift to social norms, because it shelters us and it protects us.

10:03.840 --> 10:11.280
It's not a bad thing, it's just, it's structural to the human condition. But thankfully in life,

10:11.280 --> 10:17.840
we have breakdown experiences, where that comfortable facade collapses and we're forced

10:17.840 --> 10:25.200
to confront ourselves and face who we are. And that's why anxiety conditions, whether you call

10:25.200 --> 10:30.720
it anxiety, if you're Kierkegaard or Nazia, if you're Sard, or absurdity, if you're Camus,

10:32.080 --> 10:40.080
or the horror of the nothing, if you're Nietzsche, all of these experiences are edifying

10:40.080 --> 10:47.440
experiences because they jolt us out of our rootinized drift and force us to face ourselves

10:47.440 --> 10:54.320
and to face our existence. And so the existentialists do something counterintuitive, and that is

10:55.600 --> 11:00.880
they tell us that anxiety is a good thing, it's a teacher, it's not something that should be

11:00.880 --> 11:06.000
medicated necessarily, it's not something that should be controlled with cognitive behavioral

11:06.000 --> 11:11.200
therapy necessarily. That's not to say that those things shouldn't be included in a treatment plan,

11:11.840 --> 11:17.200
but we should listen and attend to those experiences because they're teaching us valuable lessons about

11:17.200 --> 11:27.600
who we are. Because I always have heard that existentialism gets a bad rep for being too focused

11:27.600 --> 11:33.680
on the negative, too focused on the dark, but I, similarly to what you've just said, have never

11:33.680 --> 11:38.640
experienced like that. There's always been a sensation that it acknowledges and explores

11:38.640 --> 11:44.160
the darker side that is inevitably going to be there, whether you're facing it or not.

11:44.160 --> 11:51.840
And actually, if you're able to explore these different philosophies, these different perspectives

11:51.840 --> 11:57.760
on the dark and really confront and really explore what that means for you, you are empowering yourself

11:57.760 --> 12:03.280
in the way that nothing, no denial or no putting it to the side will ever, ever do.

12:04.320 --> 12:09.040
And that's one of the recurring misconceptions about existentialism, that it's a dark,

12:09.680 --> 12:18.000
brooding, navel-gazing philosophy. It's not at all. The idea is when you confront death and face death,

12:18.880 --> 12:25.840
you awaken to the fact that life is not a dress rehearsal, that this is the only life you have

12:26.560 --> 12:34.480
and confronting finitude, facing anxiety, injects a measure of intensity and urgency

12:34.480 --> 12:40.560
and vitality into our existence that otherwise it wouldn't have. And this is why Nietzsche calls

12:40.560 --> 12:45.760
his philosophy a gay science. It's a happy philosophy. It's not a morbid philosophy. It's

12:45.760 --> 12:51.760
a joyful philosophy. And Kierkegaard will say the same thing, right, that when you confront death,

12:52.720 --> 12:59.520
it opens us up to how precious and poignant and fragile every moment is, because it can

12:59.520 --> 13:06.320
be snatched away from us at any time. And so in many ways existentialism, at least for me,

13:06.320 --> 13:11.280
is the most life-affirming of all philosophies. It's not a death-focused philosophy at all. It's

13:13.280 --> 13:18.000
reminding us of how precious each moment is and that we can't take any day for granted.

13:18.640 --> 13:28.720
Now I jumped straight into existential philosophies and I am not as familiar with other philosophies.

13:28.720 --> 13:35.680
So how would you distinguish between what differentiates existential philosophies from

13:35.680 --> 13:43.840
other philosophies? Well, I mean, just in terms of academic specialties, in Anglo-American

13:43.840 --> 13:51.840
philosophy, existentialism is completely marginalized because it doesn't focus on the

13:51.840 --> 13:59.440
core issues of truth and knowledge and the nature of reality and what is the best,

13:59.440 --> 14:04.960
what is good conduct, what ought we to do. Existentialism doesn't care about any of that

14:04.960 --> 14:11.840
generally because the concern is not on philosophical abstractions. What is the

14:11.840 --> 14:16.800
nature of beauty, truth, justice, the good life? No, actually that's not true. They're concerned

14:16.800 --> 14:22.800
with the good life. The existentialist is concerned with what does it mean to be human?

14:22.800 --> 14:28.880
What is existence? And so what the existentialists do is they shift the philosophical orientation

14:28.880 --> 14:35.120
away from theoretical detachment where we theorize about abstract forms and turn our

14:35.120 --> 14:40.960
attention to the concrete flesh and blood particulars of everyday life, which is what

14:41.040 --> 14:52.960
existence engages or is involved in. And so it's a complete reversal of the traditional

14:52.960 --> 15:00.400
philosophical orientation that we inherit from Plato and Aristotle and that gets refined and

15:00.400 --> 15:09.760
consolidated with figures like Descartes and Kant. It's not a philosophy rooted in theoretical

15:09.760 --> 15:18.240
reflection, it's a philosophy rooted in attentiveness to the concreteness of our existence, of our

15:18.240 --> 15:26.960
being. And that means it focuses on the way we live every day, the moods we feel, the affective

15:26.960 --> 15:33.680
experiences that shape us and shock us into awareness like those anxiety moods or nausea moods.

15:34.480 --> 15:45.360
And so it's always been a kind of peripheral fringe philosophy in the UK and the United States,

15:45.360 --> 15:52.160
obviously less so in the Golden Age of French philosophy and German philosophy in the 20s

15:52.160 --> 16:03.360
and 30s and teens. But thankfully that's starting to change. And one of the drivers of this change

16:03.440 --> 16:11.120
is a recognition that because existentialism focuses on concrete existence, it can expand the

16:11.120 --> 16:19.760
philosophical perspective to include voices that have been traditionally marginalized in the

16:19.760 --> 16:27.120
philosophical mainstream. So feminist philosophy, of course, was in many ways inaugurated by Simone

16:27.120 --> 16:35.040
de Beauvoir. Critical race theory was deeply impacted by Frans Fanon who was a student of

16:35.040 --> 16:42.480
Sartre and Beauvoir's and was influenced by Maurice Merleau-Ponte. And so these other forms of

16:43.120 --> 16:51.440
philosophical approach that have never had a voice at the table are finally being seen as

16:51.440 --> 16:59.360
bona fide philosophical perspectives that in my view are in many ways indebted to existentialism

17:00.160 --> 17:06.480
by focusing on the concrete and the particular instead of abstract universal forms or essences.

17:08.880 --> 17:15.600
I know this is me speaking from a completely biased perspective but I hear when you say that it

17:15.600 --> 17:24.320
makes me find it hard to imagine why other philosophies have the ability to matter if we

17:24.320 --> 17:29.920
haven't understood what it is to be ourselves. If we haven't understood the kind of existential

17:29.920 --> 17:36.160
aspect of existence, why does it matter what's right or wrong if we don't know what we are?

17:36.800 --> 17:43.920
Yeah, I totally agree. I mean, I find most of Anglophone philosophy quite boring and uninteresting

17:43.920 --> 17:52.080
because of that. And as a teacher, the classes that excite the students and engage the students

17:52.080 --> 17:58.240
and inspire the students are existentially themed courses because they're at that stage in life where

17:58.240 --> 18:03.760
they're asking those questions. What am I doing? What is it about? Why am I majoring in this and

18:03.760 --> 18:10.880
not in that? And how is this going to shape the future of my life? And so when we start talking

18:10.880 --> 18:17.840
about Friedrich Nietzsche or Martin Heidegger or Jean-Paul Saag, the students resonate to these

18:17.840 --> 18:25.200
questions because they're feeling them right now at age 18, 19, 20, 21 and they're going to have to

18:25.200 --> 18:34.080
confront those really serious concerns. They're not so passionate about abstract metaphysical

18:34.080 --> 18:39.760
speculation. Those are interesting and curious thought puzzles but they're curious in the same

18:39.760 --> 18:46.240
way that I'm curious about getting good at chess or figuring out the New York Times crossword puzzle.

18:47.120 --> 18:53.840
Those thought experiments or philosophical curiosities don't keep me up at night. They don't

18:53.840 --> 18:58.880
wake me up at 3 a.m. where I'm jolted awake and I think what's the meaning of my life? That's

18:58.880 --> 19:06.080
existentialism. That's more important. Yeah, there's a difference between intellectual

19:07.040 --> 19:14.240
fascination, intellectual curiosity and kind of an inherent questioning that you're saying

19:14.240 --> 19:21.040
kind of innately surfaces at certain times of life you're saying and in certain experiences,

19:21.040 --> 19:27.760
for example, this really life-shattering or life-questioning experiences. Yeah, exactly.

19:29.440 --> 19:34.160
And we have been obviously discussing the phenomenon but we have not been defining the

19:34.240 --> 19:41.360
phenomenon. If that is possible, how would you define it? Well, existentialism as a technical

19:41.360 --> 19:50.640
term is almost beyond a clear definition and it's an ism, as I write in my book, that really

19:51.760 --> 19:58.640
is misleading. It's not like rationalism or empiricism or or scientism or naturalism.

19:59.440 --> 20:03.520
It doesn't refer to a unified philosophical school

20:06.000 --> 20:12.320
and the word wasn't introduced until the 1940s by Gabriel Marcell and

20:13.280 --> 20:20.720
Marcell used that word to refer to the philosophies of Sartre and Beauvoir but existentialism as a

20:20.720 --> 20:26.400
word didn't exist in the 19th century so Kierkegaard and Nietzsche and Dostoevsky and Tolstoy,

20:26.480 --> 20:35.120
the word didn't even exist. But I think to get a sense of the overall contours of what the word

20:35.120 --> 20:46.160
refers to, it refers to a philosophical focus on what it means to be human. What does it mean

20:46.160 --> 20:53.920
for a human being to exist? And the idea is that we exist in a way that's fundamentally different

20:53.920 --> 21:02.480
from the way this water bottle exists or this cell phone exists. We are not substances, we're not

21:02.480 --> 21:11.200
static things that are objectively present to be studied. We are activities or processes or

21:11.200 --> 21:21.920
happenings so existence is an event for humans. It's an event of self-making or self-fashioning.

21:22.480 --> 21:29.120
We make ourselves who we are through the meaning-giving choices that we undertake

21:29.120 --> 21:35.120
as our lives unfold. And this is what Sartre means when he says existence precedes essence.

21:36.080 --> 21:43.920
There is no pre-given essence that determines who we are. We make ourselves who we are by

21:44.720 --> 21:51.840
choices, by actions. And those actions are always constrained by our embodiment,

21:51.840 --> 22:00.160
our social historical situation, our gendered or sexual situation. So it's not as if our

22:01.360 --> 22:09.920
self-created, the activity of self-creation is completely unhinged. It's not completely undetermined.

22:09.920 --> 22:17.280
It's situated and constrained by what the existentialists call facticity, the facticity of

22:17.280 --> 22:27.280
who we are. And so what we do as humans is we are in a struggle or a tension between the

22:27.280 --> 22:34.320
givens of our situation and our capacity to interpret and give meaning to those givens.

22:34.320 --> 22:41.200
And the existentialists call that transcendence. So we're always in this tension between transcendence

22:41.200 --> 22:49.840
and facticity. And that struggle is existence itself, right? I'm giving meaning to the fact that

22:49.840 --> 22:57.040
I'm a man in the 21st century who's white and middle class and for the time being ambulatory

22:57.040 --> 23:03.280
and able-bodied. And I'm going to have to interpret and give meaning to that factical determination

23:03.280 --> 23:10.960
as it changes and shifts and is modified throughout the course of my life. And of course what that

23:10.960 --> 23:19.200
means is that the process of self-making is finite. It's temporal. It comes to an end. In other words,

23:19.200 --> 23:26.640
we make ourselves who we are with the recognition that that process of self-making is finite,

23:26.640 --> 23:34.480
that we are beings on the way towards death. And we don't like that. That scares us. So oftentimes

23:34.480 --> 23:42.560
we live in a way that is in denial or flight from our own finitude, from our own mortality.

23:43.120 --> 23:49.680
And that's why most of our lives are inauthentic, or in the words of Sartre and Beauvoir, in bad faith.

23:50.240 --> 23:56.720
We live in a state of self-deception most of our lives. And we think in the course of our lives

23:56.720 --> 24:03.920
that there's something real and enduring and lasting about our existence. But the existentialists

24:03.920 --> 24:08.160
want to remind us that there is nothing real, enduring or lasting about our existence. Our

24:08.160 --> 24:14.000
existence is finite. And that's not a bad thing. It's just part of what it means to be human,

24:14.000 --> 24:21.040
and we need to kind of own up to that. And so central to that process of authentic self-creation

24:21.600 --> 24:28.640
is a kind of honesty, that we need to be honest with ourselves and cut away all of the layers of

24:28.640 --> 24:37.440
self-deception that we carry with ourselves to protect us from the horror of our finitude,

24:37.440 --> 24:43.120
the horror of our contingency. So one of the things that the existentialists say is that

24:44.080 --> 24:51.360
we exist, but we don't have to exist. There's no reason for us to exist. We just happen to be

24:51.360 --> 24:59.120
thrown into existence. And against the backdrop of our thrownness, we now have to make ourselves

24:59.120 --> 25:06.320
into who we are. And that's a huge burden. That's the burden of freedom. It's dizzying and anxiety

25:06.320 --> 25:11.920
provoking. And we don't like to accept that either. And that's why we like to be told what to do.

25:11.920 --> 25:15.680
We like our priests to tell us what to do, our therapists to tell us what to do, our pop

25:15.680 --> 25:21.520
psychologists to tell us how to live our lives. We don't want to do it on our own. And of course,

25:21.520 --> 25:28.160
what the existentialists want to say is, you're always on your own anyway. You've got to be honest

25:28.160 --> 25:40.160
with yourself. So that's the cliff notes version of existentialism. Hard to define, but there are

25:40.720 --> 25:48.720
kind of central features built into it. Freedom, authenticity, temporality, all of these things

25:48.720 --> 25:55.120
kind of undergird all of the existentialist philosophers. The problem, unfortunately, is that

25:56.560 --> 26:01.760
some of the most significant voices in existentialism aren't philosophers at all.

26:02.480 --> 26:09.520
They're novelists like Dostoevsky and Tolstoy. They're poets like Reiner Maria Rilke. They're

26:09.520 --> 26:18.800
filmmakers like Akira Kurosawa. They're playwrights like Sartre and novelists like Beauvoir. And so

26:20.160 --> 26:29.440
existentialism expands far beyond the academic world. It's not exclusive to philosophers.

26:29.680 --> 26:37.200
It's open to anyone who's sincerely concerned about the human condition and is anxious about

26:37.200 --> 26:42.720
what it means to be human and is trying to articulate and express that anxiety or that concern.

26:43.600 --> 26:50.160
And there are also religious existentialists and atheistic existentialists. And so not all

26:51.040 --> 27:01.920
existentialists are following Nietzsche's maxim that God is dead. Many of the most important

27:01.920 --> 27:07.040
existentialists were theistic existentialists like Dostoevsky, like Paul Tillich, like Martin

27:07.040 --> 27:12.080
Buber. And there are some existentialists that don't believe in free will, like Nietzsche. He

27:12.080 --> 27:17.760
thinks free will is a fiction. It's an illusion. But most existentialists have some conception

27:17.840 --> 27:25.600
of freedom, of free will. And so this is why it's so difficult to demarcate the boundaries

27:25.600 --> 27:33.600
of what existentialism is. Yet there are these familiar names that are

27:34.880 --> 27:40.320
going to generally be coming across when you're studying it, especially from an academic point

27:40.640 --> 27:48.880
of view. And it's making me think who, how, how did these particular names get selected and

27:48.880 --> 27:55.840
put into the textbooks? And why are they the ones kind of being regurgitated and shared,

27:55.840 --> 28:01.200
not that there's anything not completely marvelous about what they're sharing and that they shouldn't

28:01.200 --> 28:09.040
be shared? But why them? Why not anyone else? Because they're the ones that do it. They're the

28:09.040 --> 28:16.880
ones that engage the human condition in the most powerful and accessible and visceral way.

28:17.600 --> 28:24.400
And so other novelists may talk about the human condition in certain ways, but very few do it the

28:24.400 --> 28:30.720
way Dostoevsky does it, in crime and punishment or in the Brothers Karamazah. Very few articulate

28:30.720 --> 28:36.560
the experience of confronting death like Tolstoy does and the death of Ivan Iliac. Very few capture

28:37.120 --> 28:44.720
the despair in the face of the dizzying abyss of existence like Soren Kierkegaard does and

28:44.720 --> 28:53.840
sickness unto death. So these are the figures that engage the human condition in the most powerful

28:53.840 --> 29:02.160
way. But there are other marginal figures or figures on the periphery that do it in different

29:02.160 --> 29:09.440
ways. But in my view, they may not do it as well. And or some may not have been discovered yet,

29:09.440 --> 29:17.360
who knows. But when it comes to the major figures, they're major for a reason. Because their legacy

29:17.360 --> 29:26.640
